  220: {
    beginner: `Selection Bias = Selection of individuals, groups or data for analysis in such a way that proper randomization is not achieved.`,
    detail: `Selection Bias

Description:
Selection of individuals, groups or data for analysis in such a way that proper randomization is not achieved.
The people you don't hear from change the whole story.

Example (question)
« Biased sampling in surveys. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument draws a conclusion from a sample that doesn't represent the whole group.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Missing data is just as important as visible data.
- A flawed sample guarantees a flawed result.
- You cannot generalize if the group was hand-picked.

Key concept inside it
Representative Sample:
A subset of a population that accurately reflects the members of the entire population.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Missing data is just as important as visible data.
- A flawed sample guarantees a flawed result.
- You cannot generalize if the group was hand-picked.

The uncomfortable implication
You only see the winners, so you think winning is easy.

One-line version
Selection Bias = Selection of individuals, groups or data for analysis in such a way that proper randomization is not achieved.`,
  },
