  229: {
    beginner: `Sunk Cost Fallacy = Continuing a behavior or endeavor as a result of previously invested resources.`,
    detail: `Sunk Cost Fallacy

Description:
Continuing a behavior or endeavor as a result of previously invested resources.
Throwing good money after bad.

Example (question)
« I've already spent $100 on this broken car, so I might as well spend another $100 to fix it. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument uses past, unrecoverable investments to justify future, irrational spending.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Past costs cannot be recovered.
- Only future costs and benefits should matter.
- Quitting is sometimes the most rational choice.

Key concept inside it
Unrecoverable Cost:
An investment of money, time, or effort that has already been made and cannot be recovered.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Past costs cannot be recovered.
- Only future costs and benefits should matter.
- Quitting is sometimes the most rational choice.

The uncomfortable implication
You can trap yourself in a mistake just because you spent a long time making it.

One-line version
Sunk Cost Fallacy = Continuing a behavior or endeavor as a result of previously invested resources.`,
  },
