  232: {
    beginner: `Gambler's Fallacy = The belief that if a particular event occurs more frequently than normal during the past it is less likely to happen in the future.`,
    detail: `Gambler's Fallacy

Description:
The belief that if a particular event occurs more frequently than normal during the past it is less likely to happen in the future.
The universe doesn't have a memory.

Example (question)
« Red had come up six times in a row on the roulette wheel, so Greg knew that it was time for black to come up. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument assumes that a streak in a random process changes the odds of the next event.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Past random events do not affect future random events.
- The odds reset every time.
- A long streak of bad luck does not mean you are 'due' for a win.

Key concept inside it
Independent Events:
Events where the outcome of one does not affect the outcome of the other.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Past random events do not affect future random events.
- The odds reset every time.
- A long streak of bad luck does not mean you are 'due' for a win.

The uncomfortable implication
You can lose all your money waiting for the universe to balance the scales.

One-line version
Gambler's Fallacy = The belief that if a particular event occurs more frequently than normal during the past it is less likely to happen in the future.`,
  },
  233: {
    beginner: `Gambler's Fallacy = The belief that if a particular event occurs more frequently than normal during the past it is less likely to happen in the future.`,
    detail: `Gambler's Fallacy

Description:
The belief that if a particular event occurs more frequently than normal during the past it is less likely to happen in the future.
The universe doesn't have a memory.

Example (question)
« I haven't won the lottery in 10 years, so I'm due for a win. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument assumes that a streak in a random process changes the odds of the next event.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Past random events do not affect future random events.
- The odds reset every time.
- A long streak of bad luck does not mean you are 'due' for a win.

Key concept inside it
Independent Events:
Events where the outcome of one does not affect the outcome of the other.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Past random events do not affect future random events.
- The odds reset every time.
- A long streak of bad luck does not mean you are 'due' for a win.

The uncomfortable implication
You can lose all your money waiting for the universe to balance the scales.

One-line version
Gambler's Fallacy = The belief that if a particular event occurs more frequently than normal during the past it is less likely to happen in the future.`,
  },
