  295: {
    beginner: `Vacuous Truth = A statement that is true merely because the antecedent cannot be satisfied.`,
    detail: `Vacuous Truth

Description:
A statement that is true merely because the antecedent cannot be satisfied.
Technically true, practically useless.

Example (question)
« True but meaningless statements. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument makes a claim about an empty set or a situation that doesn't exist, which makes the statement logically true but entirely meaningless.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- A statement about 'all unicorns' is always true because there are no unicorns.
- It creates the illusion of providing information.
- It is a logic trick used to sound correct without taking any real stance.

Key concept inside it
Empty Set:
A category or group that contains no items or members.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- A statement about 'all unicorns' is always true because there are no unicorns.
- It creates the illusion of providing information.
- It is a logic trick used to sound correct without taking any real stance.

The uncomfortable implication
You can win an argument by saying something that is logically undeniable but completely irrelevant.

One-line version
Vacuous Truth = A statement that is true merely because the antecedent cannot be satisfied.`,
  },
