  298: {
    beginner: `Ecological Fallacy = Thinking that relationships observed for groups necessarily hold for individuals.`,
    detail: `Ecological Fallacy

Description:
Thinking that relationships observed for groups necessarily hold for individuals.
Groups aren't individuals.

Example (question)
« People from that city are rich. You are from that city. Therefore, you must be rich. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument assumes that an individual has the exact characteristics of the statistical average of the group they belong to.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Averages hide individual differences.
- A wealthy country still has poor citizens.
- Applying group statistics to one person is mathematically invalid.

Key concept inside it
Aggregation Bias:
The false assumption that what is true for the whole must be true for all of its parts.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Averages hide individual differences.
- A wealthy country still has poor citizens.
- Applying group statistics to one person is mathematically invalid.

The uncomfortable implication
You will misjudge almost everyone if you treat them like the statistical average of their demographic.

One-line version
Ecological Fallacy = Thinking that relationships observed for groups necessarily hold for individuals.`,
  },
