  307: {
    beginner: `Cryptomnesia = A form of misattribution where a memory is mistaken for imagination.`,
    detail: `Cryptomnesia

Description:
A form of misattribution where a memory is mistaken for imagination.
Plagiarism by accident.

Example (question)
« Thinking an idea is original when it's from memory. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument presents an idea or memory as original, when in reality it is a forgotten memory of someone else's idea.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- The brain remembers the idea but forgets the source.
- It leads to unintentional plagiarism.
- It feels exactly like a stroke of original genius.

Key concept inside it
Source Amnesia:
The inability to remember where, when, or how previously learned information was acquired.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- The brain remembers the idea but forgets the source.
- It leads to unintentional plagiarism.
- It feels exactly like a stroke of original genius.

The uncomfortable implication
Your most brilliant, original idea might just be something you read on Twitter three years ago.

One-line version
Cryptomnesia = A form of misattribution where a memory is mistaken for imagination.`,
  },
