  328: {
    beginner: `Hard-Easy Effect = The tendency to overestimate one's performance on easy tasks and underestimate it on hard tasks.`,
    detail: `Hard-Easy Effect

Description:
The tendency to overestimate one's performance on easy tasks and underestimate it on hard tasks.
Overconfident on hard tasks, underconfident on easy ones.

Example (question)
« Thinking I did well on a simple test. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument exhibits a cognitive bias where people overestimate their ability to solve difficult problems and underestimate their ability to solve easy ones.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- We assume we can beat the odds on impossible tasks.
- We doubt ourselves on tasks everyone else finds simple.
- It skews our perception of risk and reward.

Key concept inside it
Dunning-Kruger Effect (related):
A cognitive bias where people with limited knowledge or competence greatly overestimate their own knowledge or competence.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- We assume we can beat the odds on impossible tasks.
- We doubt ourselves on tasks everyone else finds simple.
- It skews our perception of risk and reward.

The uncomfortable implication
You will bet your life savings on a lottery ticket but refuse to fix a leaky faucet.

One-line version
Hard-Easy Effect = The tendency to overestimate one's performance on easy tasks and underestimate it on hard tasks.`,
  },
