  331: {
    beginner: `Herd Mentality = The tendency for individuals to follow the actions or thinking of a larger group.`,
    detail: `Herd Mentality

Description:
The tendency for individuals to follow the actions or thinking of a larger group.
Following the crowd right off a cliff.

Example (question)
« Buying a stock because everyone else is. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument adopts a belief or behavior simply because many other people are doing it.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- There is safety in numbers, but not necessarily truth.
- It drives financial bubbles and panic buying.
- People stop thinking independently.

Key concept inside it
Bandwagon Effect:
The tendency to do or believe things because many other people do or believe the same.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- There is safety in numbers, but not necessarily truth.
- It drives financial bubbles and panic buying.
- People stop thinking independently.

The uncomfortable implication
You will abandon your own common sense if enough people around you act crazy.

One-line version
Herd Mentality = The tendency for individuals to follow the actions or thinking of a larger group.`,
  },
