  337: {
    beginner: `Hot-Hand Fallacy = The belief that a person who has experienced success with a random event has a greater chance of further success in additional attempts.`,
    detail: `Hot-Hand Fallacy

Description:
The belief that a person who has experienced success with a random event has a greater chance of further success in additional attempts.
Streaks are just math, not magic.

Example (question)
« Thinking a basketball player on a streak will keep scoring. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument assumes that a person who has experienced success has a greater chance of further success in additional attempts.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Randomness is clumpy.
- A coin flipping heads five times doesn't 'want' to flip heads again.
- It leads to terrible gambling and investment decisions.

Key concept inside it
Clustering Illusion:
The tendency to erroneously consider the inevitable 'streaks' or 'clusters' arising in small samples from random distributions to be non-random.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Randomness is clumpy.
- A coin flipping heads five times doesn't 'want' to flip heads again.
- It leads to terrible gambling and investment decisions.

The uncomfortable implication
You will lose your money betting that a lucky streak is a permanent skill.

One-line version
Hot-Hand Fallacy = The belief that a person who has experienced success with a random event has a greater chance of further success in additional attempts.`,
  },
