  373: {
    beginner: `Outcome Bias = The tendency to judge a decision by its outcome rather than by the quality of the decision at the time it was made.`,
    detail: `Outcome Bias

Description:
The tendency to judge a decision by its outcome rather than by the quality of the decision at the time it was made.
A stupid decision that gets lucky is still a stupid decision.

Example (question)
« Calling a risky decision bad if it fails. »
This is the exact kind of move the question is testing.

Example (everyday)
The argument judges the quality of a decision based purely on its eventual outcome, rather than the information available at the time the decision was made.
The same logic shows up even when the surface story changes.

How it works
The argument uses the surface clue as if it were enough to settle the claim.

So:
- Drunk driving is a bad choice even if you get home safely.
- We reward lucky fools and punish unlucky experts.
- It destroys rational risk management.

Key concept inside it
Hindsight Bias (related):
The tendency, after an event has occurred, to see the event as having been predictable.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- Drunk driving is a bad choice even if you get home safely.
- We reward lucky fools and punish unlucky experts.
- It destroys rational risk management.

The uncomfortable implication
You will eventually destroy yourself if you think your lucky wins prove you are a genius.

One-line version
Outcome Bias = The tendency to judge a decision by its outcome rather than by the quality of the decision at the time it was made.`,
  },
